

## LANDING 4 — EIENTEI

They land in bamboo.

Tall, dense, identical in every direction. The kind of place where losing the path means losing everything. The air is still and thick and green-tinted from the canopy. Somewhere nearby, something moves in the stalks and then doesn't.

Then the bamboo parts — deliberately — and someone is already running toward them.

Moon-rabbit ears. A military-style uniform. A medical kit already open in her hands.

She reaches them, checks the nearest person for injuries before saying a word, and then looks up with an expression that is professionally neutral over something that might be relief.

> "You're not hurt. Good. That's — good. We don't have a lot of time, this forest isn't safe after dark and we have about two hours. Can you walk? All of you?"

Her name is Reisen Udongein Inaba. She was sent to retrieve them. The fact that she was already on her way before they arrived is something she doesn't explain yet.

She leads them through the bamboo at a pace that makes clear she knows exactly where she's going and expects them to keep up.

Eientei appears as a set of lights in the dark, then a gate, then a courtyard, then an interior that is warmer and stranger than anything a bamboo forest has any right to contain.

At the far end of a long room, a woman in elaborate robes looks up from a desk covered in instruments that have no names in any language the players know.

> "On time," Eirin says. Not to Reisen. To the players. "I expected you a little earlier, but — close enough."